<br>
<br>
&quot;When President Reagan first proposed it, the International Space Station was supposed to cost $8 billion. <br>
<br>
Through the years, that number climbed like a rocket, even though the station design shrank in size and scope. At one point, the General Accounting Office, Congress' investigative arm, estimated the bill for the orbiting research platform and the shuttle flights to support it was approaching $100 billion. <br>
<br>
Today, the Bush administration says the end of the station's construction is in sight and only $6.6 billion more is needed to get there.&quot;<br>
<br>
Let me say briefly: the ISS is a shame, nearly(?) futile, a crude mockery for all the people that is financing it (mostly of you, little green men). Do you agree with this? Or maybe you think that the ISS is one of the Wonders of Ours Times, and the Key to the Whole of the Universe... <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=prenda2@nuclearspace>prenda2</A> at: 12/1/02 4:12:40 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=zaphod4468>zaphod4468</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>ezOP</span><br>  Posts: 1579<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(12/1/02 2:22:04 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=206.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/user/zaphod2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: ISS: the crap out</span><hr size=1> ISS sux.<br>
<br>
The current problem is the fact that the Stations escape craft<br>
was cancelled, meaning that only 3 residents can stay onboard<br>
because they are using Russian Soyuz craft for an escape system<br>
and that's all it can hold... 3 people.<br>
<br>
Now here is the problem with 3 people (and not 7). It takes 2.5 <br>
people hours to maintain the station, leaving one half a person <br>
hours to perform any experiments!<br>
<br>
What a waste.  <br>
<br>
I say we strap a nuclear rocket on it and send it to Mars! <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=hamster@nuclearspace>Hamster</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 500<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(12/1/02 2:53:58 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=206.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://image1ex.villagephotos.com/extern/935754.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: ISS: the crap out</span><hr size=1> Oh god, it figures that we'd spend 100 billion on a useless lemon.  They should just deorbit the thing and cut thier losses or turn it into a dedicated tourist trap.  I haven't read of any experiments that seem like they really depend on having such an expensive station.  Mir could probably have done just as well for 90% of the research being carried out.  The Internation Budget Buster as John Fraz so eloquently referred to it is nothing more than an international welfare project.   <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=johnfraz>John Fraz</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_yingyang.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Orion Commander</span><br>  Posts: 290<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(12/1/02 4:03:14 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=206.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://lneilsmith.com/tools/littlelogo.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: ISS: the crap out</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>&gt; Now here is the problem with 3 people (and<br>
not 7). It takes 2.5 people hours to maintain the<br>
station, leaving one half a person hours to perform<br>
any experiments!</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
 A good solution (and which should have been done with Mir, if there were any real probability of reconditioning it), is to launch a new volume with a Shuttle-C. A single presure volume, with everything it needs to be used, in one shot, with maybe 1/4 the cost of a Shuttle mission to put it up, plus a Shuttle mission to assemble it (unless -even better- the new volume supports EVA work).<br>
 Forget about using the Shuttle to support the ISS, unless there's anything only it can do (not likely), since the Shuttle is so expensive to use.<br>
Use the HL-20/42 to transport crew up/down, and as a lifeboat.<br>
<br>
Of course it's fantasy, since it doesn't pay NASA's payroll for the army of Shuttle ground crew, and immediately shows the Shuttle to be a lemon. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=prenda2@nuclearspace>prenda2</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Tourist</span><br>  Posts: 6<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(12/1/02 4:07:25 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=206.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: ISS: the crap out</span><hr size=1> &quot;I haven't read of any experiments that seem like they really depend on having such an expensive station.&quot;<br>
<br>
I've read that those experiments simply doesn't exist (Robert  L. Park- &quot;Woodoo Science&quot; 1999) <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=nukepulse>NukePulse</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Cadet</span><br>  Posts: 32<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(12/1/02 5:56:50 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=206.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/16.gif" align=absmiddle>  NASA 2002 MUhahahhahaha. </span><hr size=1> I call the ISS turkey the ‘International Corporate Welfare Station’ or ICWS for short. The minimum cost of sending the Golden Goose to orbit is about $1,000,000,000.00. To find the actual cost of  the ICWS add  the cost of the payloads to that bloated figure.  For STS 112 the cost is 1,000,000,000 + 385,000,000 = $1.385  for that insane stunt.<br>
<br>
The stunningly bold $1.385 billion STS-112 mission to the stars amazingly delivered a ‘structural component’ and three radiators to the corporate welfare station, WOW! If NASA can’t figure out why support for their activities is on the down swing perhaps they should have their collective noses rubbed in the fiscal mess that they dropped on the rug and then be soundly whipped around the head and shoulders with a rolled up GAO report.<br>
<br>
The Russians had MIR up for more than a decade and that working space station cost only a small fraction of what the incomplete ICWS  has to this date. If they are doing any earth shaking research on the ICWS I would sure like to know about it. The fact is that the NASA clowns actually have to dream up irrelevant dip-shite experiments to pretend that it has a purpose. <br>
<br>
The Russians being a bit on the frugal side out of necessity put the components of MIR up with the venerable but exceedingly cost effective SL-4 rocket with upper stages. That alone kept the costs down since it only costs $2,000 dollars to put a pound of payload into LEO with it as compared to the Golden Gooses 20,000 –30,000 dollars cost per pound to LEO. <br>
<br>
The ISS, the Space Shuttle, and NASA itself are the three most significant impediments to the exploration of the solar system. The money is there for real space exploration, it always has been. What isn’t there is creativity and boldness. NASA like any other diseased component of the federal bureaucracy has two main missions and they are institutional survival and growth. <br>
<br>
NASA the pathetic creature that it is could justify its own existence even if it was only launching $20.00 Estes rockets for a million dollar a pop.<br>
<br>
Look at some of NASA's screw ups:<br>
<br>
1) Remember the Hubble space telescope? It came in at only 10 times the projected cost and is was so flawed that they had to do a $1,500,000,000.00  ‘repair’ mission to put a pair of bifocals on the myopic beast. It's hard to believe but NASA sees that whole comedy of errors as a victory. <br>
<br>
2) What about the $300,000,000.00 probe to Mars that got lost because the NASA folks forgot to put a line of code in the guidance program that would convert metric units to statute units. <br>
<br>
3) Then there is the $400,000,000.00 failed soft landing on mars not too long ago. That sure was a far cry from the NASA that landed the Vikings in Mars. The sweet part is that a senior NASA official passed it off as 'the price of doing business.'<br>
<br>
4) Then a bit further back it was the failed launch of a Delta rocket with a $300,000,000.00 interplanetary probe on it. The Delta being a mutated and overpriced 1950's vintage IRBM should have been retired long ago. Perhaps if NASA wasn't grafted to the shuttle like a piss bum is to his bottle of cheap wine we would have newer more powerful and reliable ELV's. <br>
<br>
<br>
